column12:
395213818 @stevegal - which map have you tried? matthewbeasley
395218589 It's not a problem with the map itself. Generics in Java are type erased at runtime as I'm sure you know. I did a build on my mac with `mvn clean install` and got a `incompatible types: inference variable V has incompatible bounds
    equality constraints: com.capitalone.dashboard.evaluator.Evaluator
    lower bounds: ? extends com.capitalone.dashboard.evaluator.Evaluator<? extends com.capitalone.dashboard.response.AuditReviewResponse<? extends java.lang.Enum<? extends java.lang.Enum<?>>>>,U`

when it is building `src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/model/DashboardAuditModel.java:[54,43] ` in that module. 

Obviously it works in the linux build in Travis, and once built I'm sure the bytecode works. 
However if you either cast each typed evaluator to the base evaulator (eg... `new SimpleEntry<>(AuditType.CODE_REVIEW, (Evaluator)codeReviewEvaluator)`) then it will all work. 

However, I personally dislike using streams in this way as its not the simplest thing that works. If you have a fixed map, then build it without the stream complication.

 stevegal
395220320 I've done a PR (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/2266) with the type 1 fix,
and an alternative one with the (imho) simpler straight map version (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/2267) stevegal
407536856 Closing this as you resolved the issue and created a pr Sbrenthughes

but a smaller more focussed list. To do this you can now use filtering on
the aws side to describe only the instances that match your filter.

We are using JIRA (Cloud) and not using any teams. Will this JIRA collector work without teams? I am not able to get anything to show up.

When selecting the widget in the UI you have to select a team (but none show for our setup).

The documentation references:
> If your JIRA instance uses Boards as Teams (instead of the Teams plugin), then set feature.jiraBoardAsTeam property to true.

So does this imply that false really does turn it off completely? I have the properties set to false now.

Documentation also references:
> Check the JIRA URL to see if you are getting any team data in response. Example JIRA URL: https://your-jira-base-url/rest/agile/1.0/board?startAt=0.

Using the above api call - I do get a 50 out of 135 results, but nothing references "team".

column2:
I'm facing with a problem: 
  We had used the jenkins pipeline job to deploy our apps for a while, and these days I was trying to add the 
snippets generated by `Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin` to the pipeline code, and I was able to pubilsh the deploy steps to Hygieia Dashboard, however, the dashboard was red, and the deploy order wasn't right ether, see below:
 - jenkins pipeline steps
  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40772554-dccc9e62-64f2-11e8-8c05-cb180ef86c15.png)

- Hygieia dashboard widget
  ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40772616-0acabfba-64f3-11e8-8e0a-3f3e4fac3e59.png)

Please help.

And there is an other question, as it is described here [Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin](https://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.html), the `mvn clean package` will generate to files: `hygieia-publisher.hpi` and `hygieia-publisher.jar`, so, what's the use of `hygieia-publisher.jar`?  Or should it be used and how can I use it ?


Best regards & thanks a lot.
column5: The deploy order published by Hygieia-Jenkins Plugin doesn't right
column12:
393470702 Does anyone meet this before ? Any help would be great appreciation. ykfq
393498997 I hava figured out why the widget is red.
The `hygieiaDeployPublishStep: Hygieia Deployment Publish Step` has many build status, when the deployment is success, we should publish `Success` from jenkins pipeline to hygieia.  
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20741596/40779475-ba5c354e-6507-11e8-87be-04543aefc429.png)
 ykfq
393499595 But is the order a problem ?  I've found that the screenshots of official is also disorderd
see [here](https://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/media/images/Screenshots/hygiea-screenshot.jpg) ykfq
398197917 It would probably be nice to have some sort of order there.  I am going to close the issue since you seem to have it resolved.  Sbrenthughes

column2:
Hi,
We have ldap authentication active on our Jenkins install (not using Jenkins local user db).
I'm trying to configure the jenkins build collector but it always fails with:

```
2018-05-28 10:30:00,225 INFO  c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Error getting jobs for: http://our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/ 0s
2018-05-28 10:30:00,228 ERROR c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - client exception loading jobs
org.springframework.web.client.HttpClientErrorException: 401 Invalid password/token for user: myuser
```

Though, I can see all jobs when configuring the build widget.

The application.properties file:

```
dbname=dashboarddb
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
dbreplicaset=false
dbhostport=localhost:27017,127.0.0.1:27017,ip-10-100-9-120:27017
dbusername=dbuser
dbpassword=password
jenkins.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
jenkins.pageSize=1000
jenkins.folderDepth=10
jenkins.servers[0]=http://our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/
jenkins.usernames[0]=myuser
jenkins.apiKeys[0]=b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745
jenkins.saveLog=false
jenkins.searchFields[0]= options.jobName
jenkins.searchFields[1]= niceName
```

Is it not possible to use an ldap accout with a token?

Thank you
Tomas
column5: Jenkis Build Collector with ldap user and token fails
column12:
392595776 @xhostAB can you try this way 
jenkins.servers[0]=http://myuser:b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745@our.jenkins.server.tld:8080/

remove 
jenkins.usernames[0]=myuser
jenkins.apiKeys[0]=b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745

how you got this apiKey - b344df0bfd19352f2a2cf4046eaa1745 ? nireeshT
392665792 @nireeshT thanks did try that too (forgot to mention), but I got it working after I added the jenkins url and account in the dashboard under Admin -> General Configuration -> Hudson
Not sure why there are two settings? application.properties and in the dashboard? xhostAB
392783943 We are working to move away from properties files as much as possible. Hopefully, in the near future, Hygieia would only need to know the db credentials via properties file or some other method. The rest of the properties would be stored in the database.  Sbrenthughes

## Summary

Build failure due to inability to download tarball.

**Update**: The URL is for `http`, when npm switched to `https`, and the plug-in (`eirslett/frontend-maven-plugin`) doesn't seem to support redirects from http to https.

## Configuration

* Ubuntu 14.04 Trusty Tahr (clean)
* Java 1.8.0_171-b11
* Maven 3.3.9

## Steps

1. Install Oracle Java 1.8.0
2. Install Maven - `apt-get install maven`
3. cd /path/to/hygieia
4. `mvn clean install package`

## Expected Results

As per instructions, expected it to not error: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html.

This error seems to be related to downloading using: `http://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz`.  The mechanism to download this is not working.

## Actual Results

```
INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[INFO] BUILD FAILURE
[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[INFO] Total time: 16:33 min
[INFO] Finished at: 2018-05-28T01:40:52+00:00
[INFO] Final Memory: 121M/241M
[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[ERROR] Failed to execute goal com.github.eirslett:frontend-maven-plugin:0.0.29:install-node-and-npm (install node and npm) on project UI: Could not download npm: Could not download http://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz: Unknown host registry.npmjs.org: Name or service not known -> [Help 1]
[ERROR]
[ERROR] To see the full stack trace of the errors, re-run Maven with the -e switch.
[ERROR] Re-run Maven using the -X switch to enable full debug logging.
[ERROR]
[ERROR] For more information about the errors and possible solutions, please read the following articles:
[ERROR] [Help 1] http://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/MAVEN/MojoFailureException
[ERROR]
[ERROR] After correcting the problems, you can resume the build with the command
[ERROR]   mvn <goals> -rf :UI
```
## NOTES

When I curl manually, I noticed a 301:

```
HTTP/1.1 301 Moved Permanently
Date: Mon, 28 May 2018 01:53:03 GMT
Transfer-Encoding: chunked
Connection: keep-alive
Cache-Control: max-age=3600
Expires: Mon, 28 May 2018 02:53:03 GMT
Location: https://registry.npmjs.org/npm/-/npm-5.0.1.tgz
Server: cloudflare
CF-RAY: 421d15dc46c76d66-SJC
```

Build failure due to module not compatible with system Maven.  The documentation does not specify any version of Maven so I used the default.  Might want to make this clear in the docs, little to nothing on requirements.

## Configuration

* Ubuntu 14.04 Trusty Tahr (clean)
* Java 1.8.0_171-b11

## Steps

1. Install Oracle Java 1.8.0
2. Install Maven - `apt-get install maven`
3. cd /path/to/hygieia
4. `mvn clean install package`

## Expected Results

As per instructions, expected it to not error: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html

If a particular version of Java and/or Maven are required, then expected this would be documented in setup.

## Actual Results

```

column5: adding updated sonar interface to fetch for Sonar 5.6.7 with more than 500 projects

column2:
As of Sonar 6.2 the /api/resource sonar qube is removed. There's various limits on this (500 projects fetch etc.) in previous versions (could only test with 5.6.7).

Proper channel would be to fetch via /api/projects.
See my example PR. It's a simple fix, but didn't go to far in modifying existing logic.

391009743 @Neumsy - could you provide more information about the specific failure that occurred and what you did to fix it? matthewbeasley
391060043 I received an error message running mvn install on the project that it could not find some of the spring http classes on the core module.  To resolve the issue, I added a dependency to the spring-web module in the core/pom.xml file.  

This may be due to the spring-web being a transitive dependency and we are behind a corporate firewall with an internal Maven/Artifactory repository.  Adding the dependency loaded it into our internal repository which now works correctly on a new build.

Unfortunately since I resolved the issue, I cannot duplicate the error message I saw.  But this is what I added to the pom.xml file:

```
<dependency>
            <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
            <artifactId>spring-web</artifactId>
</dependency>
``` Neumsy

I am trying to collect data from SonarQube hosted server v6.7.1. I provided properties file as described here: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/sonar.html but there's no clue about how to authenticate on the Sonar server. Our server requires auth to read any data.

I tried to generate api token and provide `sonar.servers[0]` as `https://api-token@sonar-server` or  `https://sonar-user:api-token@sonar-server` with no use:

`c.c.d.collector.DefaultSonar6Client - org.springframework.web.client.HttpClientErrorException: 401`

Curl, wget and powershell webrequests are all reporting status 200 with URL `https://api-token@sonar-server`. I examined `SonarCollector.java` in Hygieia project but found nothing except servers, versions, and metrics. 

Is there any way to authenticate the collector on a sonar server?

Hello Everyone,

I had success in reading Commit Stage on Product Dashboard but had no luck on populating Build Stage. 
Options tried 
1.  DefaultPipeline  ( dont recall- why it wasnt showing data)
2. DynamicPipeline  (Issue: it is looking data in CodeRepos collection in creating BuildPipelineResponse and I didnt find any code that writes codeRepos from Bamboo Build Collector , where as codeRepos are being populated in Jenkins Build Collector ) -- GetBuildDetails method

I understand that the recommended way is to use Hygieia Publisher to push data into Hygieia 

Here is Collectors information 
1. Bitbucket Collector
2. Bamboo Build Collector
3. Custom Bamboo Deploy Collector

Question I have for you all out there is ?
Is Product Dashboard Pipeline has worked with Pull Strategy (using Collectors) to display data from Bitbucket, Bamboo Build

What is the recommended approach should I use Default Pipeline or DyanmicPipeline for Pull Strategy with Collectors and not using Publisher ? I am guessing it should be DynamicPipeline

column12: 391725291 @trinathtiru Are you sure your mongodb is running correctly? and the login credentials for MongoDB are correctly mentioned in the application properties . Per the above conversation, I believe you are using the below command to bring up your application? `java -jar github-collector.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=/usr/Hygieia/collectors/scm/github/application.properties` rvema 392273620 @trinathtiru @Phoenix9032 looks like there is lot of confusion going around with github.key and github.personalAccessToken github.key is value generated from core module. You can generate this key from UI as admin user. 1) create an admin user - useername - "admin" , password -"you can chose any password" 2) go to admin settings -> Generate Api token -> create new key by setting name and expiration date. 3) Copy the generated key to github properties file as github.key = "generated key". 4) Go to api.properties file, add property -> key = "generated key" 5) Generated key is used to encrypt password when you configure github repository for accessing private repos. Public repos will not require github.key or github.personalAccessToken. On the other hand, github.personal AccessToken is directly taken from github-> developer settings-> personalAccessToken. This value is used to access the private repos. You can use either github.key or github.personalAccesstoken to access private repos and they are doing the same thing. nireeshT 394731011 @trinathtiru - I think there's enough information here to answer your questions. column2:
I have a private repo on Bitbucket server (stash). I configured everything as described here: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html#encryption-for-private-repos but still got 401 error, so I decided to investigate the case before posting a new issue.

I've added `LOG.debug("decryptedPassword: " + decryptedPassword);` to `DefaultBitbucketServerClient.java` and here's what I've seen in the log: 

```
DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultBitbucketServerClient - decryptedPassword: rd
```

Guess what? My password is `rd#SomeOtherSymbolsAndDigits`. Looks like the hashtag symbol `#` ruins the decryption process. Therefore I am forced to change password or use other credentials with no `#` in the password string.

Any suggestions how to fix this? I am not a java programmer so I can't fix it myself and I really don't want to change password on a technical login.
column5: Bitbucket collector -- decryptedPassword issue
column12: 389966550 Encryption and Decryption is handle via a Java library. Hygieia doesn't manage this.  Sbrenthughes

column2: When you do a "mvn clean" in the UI directory, it ought to remove dist, node, node_modules and bower_components.  Otherwise, it's not really clean.
column5: maven clean should remove dist, node, node_modules and bower_components
column12: 392904429 @panglin - we use https://github.com/eirslett/frontend-maven-plugin for the UI portion of the build. According to the developer it's "Not meant to install Node for production uses. The Node usage is intended as part of a frontend build, running common javascript tasks such as minification, obfuscation, compression, packaging, testing etc." That being said, if you have issues with the way this plugin works you should file an issue on their github page. matthewbeasley

column2:
Hi All,
We are facing an issue wherein the dashboarduser thats created in mongodb gets deleted after a gap of 2-3 weeks causing the dashboard to disappear. This has been a recurring issue for us, all collectors, api, UI and mongodb are running on the same machine. Below are the db properties that we have been using in collectors and API:
dbname=dashboarddb
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
dbusername=dashboarduser
dbpassword=dbpassword

Once the dashboard is gone, I have to create the dashboarduser again in mongodb and then re-create the dashboards from scratch.
Please let me know if anyone else has faced a similar issue.
column5: dashboarduser gets deleted from mongodb
column12:
389756731 Check logs. Check logins, check history, etc. a db drop has nothing to do with the application. Maybe there is an exploit and some does plays with you?  cradules
389905891 @DeepakYadav17  No cleanup logic in code. Check if you recreate Mongo on server rehydration, that is one way I could think of.  nireeshT
390556181 Thanks for the responses @cradules and @nireeshT , I will check and will get back on this. DeepakYadav17
391852661 @DeepakYadav17 it would be nice to know how you installed mongodb on your localhost. If you are using docker for instance then it could be that you aren't mapping a data volume in which case the data will be lost upon container restart.  matthewbeasley

388281181 Hey,

I had same issue and I have solved it as fallow:

1. First step is to compile UI. 

cd /path/where/sourcecode/exist/UI
npm install gulp
npm install bower
npm install
bower install
mvn clean install package

2. Second step
cd /path/where/sourcecode/exist/
npm install bower
npm install
bower install
mvn clean install package

NOTE:

Dont run the compile under sudo/root. 
Create a user and compile the code under that user. 
Make sure you have installed  java 1.8 and nodejs ( I am using nodejs-10.x,.x)
Make sure all the files/folders has the owner the user you have created. 

I am building now a script to make full install and configuration for this dashboard. Soon is done I will share it.

PS:

Actually the part of the install is already covered. You can have a look over and inspire. 

https://github.com/cradules/bash_scripts/blob/master/install-hygieia.sh

The script is for RHEL 7/CeontsOS 7. Dont try to run it. The script is build with the idea of creating a new filesystem as LVM and for that you need to provide a new disk .  The script is on developing so still needs  a lot of work and I am sure of that :) cradules

column2:
Guys, fewer months later have I some time working again on Hygieia. Currently I could successfully run Hygieia on local Docker environment. Moreover, I need to move our Hygieia to AWS because the local env will be shut down.
I am here to ask if someone have good practice on run Hygieia on AWS.
Four possible ways come to my mind:

**- Option1 - EC2 - Standard**
   Run a EC2 instance and build Hygieia as same as run on a local sever without Docker

**- Option2 - EC2 - Docker**
   Install Docker in the EC2 instance then build Hygieia and do Docker-compose trick

**- Option3 - ECS - Single**
  Re-build an ALL-IN-ONE Hygieia docker image according to existing dockerfile.
  Re-configure CMD and properties and run as one ECS service

**- Option4 - ECS - Multiple**
  Run each ECS service mapping to each Hygieia 
  As I use CloudFormation to control everything in my AWS, need to define the templates according to the Docker-compose configuration.
column5: Run Hygieia on AWS
column12:
387630034 Before I would decide to deploy something I would ask myself next questions?

What is my bugged?
How do I consider the environment, prod, dev, etc?
Do I need HA (High Aveability) for my application? 
What will be the load of the servers? 


When you have the answers to this question you may be able to design the infrastructure you would need. 

Here how would go:

Low budget  + prod  = no HA and you will try to cover the downtime in the best way you can in the given conditions.

good bugged + prod = HA . For HA I would go with a cluster managed with kubernetes.
good bugged + dev = no HA, no point of wasting money!

The need of an infrastructure is not decided by the application but by the bugged and the uptime you need to provide.  cradules

Just a few general questions about the HipChat:

- Does the collector work?  I saw some conflicting issues about it working.  The collector is up and running but I am not receiving any data on my dashboard and there are no errors on the console or in the logs

- Does it populate any tables in Mongo?  If so, which ones?

- When configuring HipChat - I am assuming the following configurations:
-ChatOps Server URL - https://companyName.hipchat.com
-Room Name - the room number from the URL https://companyName.hipchat.com/chat/room/**4067442**
-Room Auth Token - token generated from HipChat API - I have tried both View Messages and View Group scopes

Thanks for the help!

kindly assist
column5: how to debug hygieia application
column12: 390760803 I use intelliJ  by creating a run/debug configuration and running in debug mode that way. I would suggest looking up how to run a spring boot application in your IDE. Once you can run it in your IDE then you can work on running in debug mode.  Sbrenthughes

I'm working with the gitlab collector and I can retrieve data from my Gitlab only the firstime when I add the repo url.
![capture2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/37840434/39519539-6f25c930-4e07-11e8-9683-379a6755ae08.JPG)

 After that data are not getting refreshed and nothing changes even when I commit many times.

![capture3](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/37840434/39519627-ce8b5ea8-4e07-11e8-8a13-0ec5bf1d7389.JPG)

What can be the problem according to you ? 
Thanks
column5: Gitlab datas are not getting refreshed in the UI
column12:
399364697 hi jhonygo
    I have the same problem, and I fix it by change GitlabUrlUtility.java line126 from
   
    dt = getDate(new Date(repo.getLastUpdated()), 0, -10);
   
    to 
   
    dt = getDate(new Date(repo.getLastUpdated()), -7, -10);

    It seems fixed the problem, now the new commits can update in the ui.
 ntvis
399531379 Hello @ntvis,

Thank you much for the tip, we rebuilt the package with @develo55 as suggested  and it worked like a charm! I hope your fix will be included in a future version soon.
Thanks again. jhonygo
401080836 @ntvis - please submit your change as a PR matthewbeasley
403308804 @ntvis : thanks it worked like charm :). MummanaSubramanya
413424054 closing due to inactivity, please reopen is this is still happening. rvema
386051139 Hello,
To complete the issue, it occured with latest core and collector against 9.1.4 on premise (community and enterprise), and gitlab.com instances.
An ugly workaround: change the setup to another branch, then switch back to the target one : all latest commits appear. Unapplicable on our real setup (hundreds repositories). jhonygo

column2:
Hello all,
After reading issue #1330 , i put this code: "hygieiaSonarPublishStep ceQueryIntervalInSeconds: '10', ceQueryMaxAttempts: '30' " wrapped in the withSonarQubeEnv {} block.

After execution,Jenkins console log says :"Hygieia: Published Build Data For Sonar Publishing. Response Code: 201. Response Value= 5ae1fe1cf5a064a0e3521ec4"

However,build fails at Sonar stage with message:

"**Hygieia Sonar Publish Step | String index out of range: -1**"

I have doubt that the parameters passed here(hygieiaSonarPublishStep ceQueryIntervalInSeconds: '10', ceQueryMaxAttempts: '30') are not sufficient and need additional details,if so ,please post this hygieiaSonarPublishStep with proper parameters or suggest a solution .

Thanks
column5: Issue while using hygieiaSonarPublishStep
column12:
385425594 @rohandora  can you try this 
hygieiaSonarPublishStep ceQueryIntervalInSeconds: 10, ceQueryMaxAttempts: 30 nireeshT
387969127 Hello @nireeshT ,
I checked with your answer,i am getting error:"Excepted string received int" .
Can we specify "hygieiaSonarPublishStep" without any values ?.
Because in that case the default values would be taken from code itself.

I tried simply putting **hygieiaSonarPublishStep** in jenkinsfile runSonar  ,which gives error.
Thanks rohandora
388026365 Worked  now,the error was happening because in setSonarDetails,getSonarProjectName() was getting partial projectName . rohandora

column2:
I am receiving a 401 Unauthorized when I run the BitBucket collector.  I was unsure if I need to encrypt the key or not.  I generated a key - https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/set-up-an-ssh-key-728138079.html and I am using it in bitbucket.key property in the application.properties file.  Here is my application.properties

git.host=bitbucket.org/
git.api=/
git.commitThresholdDays=15
git.pageSize=25
git.product=cloud
bitbucket.key==ssh-rsa AA...

In the UI - I have https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<org_name>/<repo_name> with a branch of master and no credentials

How does the the git.host, git.api and repo url all fit together?

Thanks
Mike
column5: BitBucket 401 Unauthorized

column2:
This is very basic question.
In this push based approach, I understand that we configure the Hygieia server where Jenkins needs to publish to. But it appears to be ONE static server value. Can the publish be done to a Hygieia host **dynamically** (mentioned as a parameter) as part of the publish code itself?

just curious
column5: Hygieia-Jenkins publisher question
column12:
384045141 @nireeshT 
Am using freestyle jobs for now. 
But I think my question is applicable to both freestyle or pipeline.

I do not mean the environments. 
What I mean by One static value versus Dynamic value is, The Hygieia server information that is given during the configuration (in jenkins configuration), can it be given in the publish command itself? (and thats what I meant by dynamically)

For e.g,
hygieiaBuildPublishStep buildStatus: 'InProgress' HygieiaHostSrrName:'myhygteamdashboardshost.net'
 email2niranjan
384045406 where am coming from is.. what if in our enterprise, we do not want to share the Hygieia host and we have separate hosts for each application email2niranjan
384708608 @email2niranjan  You should be able to pass a dynamic value via a build variable, I have not tried though. It should work.  nireeshT
384720665 @nireeshT 
Thanks... Does this require a  code change? Or existing build should work?
any idea what the publish parameter name should be, for a hygieia host/server name? email2niranjan
385309373 I learnt through other history posts/issues that this is not possible. Hence closing this ticket.
But I did find a way to use cURL POST commands to post statuses to apis. Hence closing this issue. email2niranjan
384043430 @email2niranjan  are you using free style or pipeline jobs.  Can you explain more on "ONE static server value". If you mean environment value like "DEV","QA"..etc, you can always pass dynamic variables in all fields. nireeshT

column2:
This PR provides the following feature:

- one centralized directory where one can put their entreprise certs
- declaration of a volume in docker-compose.yml that can be used in docker-compose.override
- readme file
- git ignore to make sure nobody uploads their certs to the public repo

One can attach the certs volume to any collector to make the crt available to the collector. Then, reuse the script block in Bitbucket's properties-builder.sh to add all the certs to the image's keystore.
column5: Centralized entreprise certificate management + addition in Bitbucket collector

column2:
Hello,

I just linked a Hygieia instance to our internal bitbucket server. To do this, I add to modify some properties-builder scripts. Typically, when using private repos, both API and the collector need to share the encryption key:

- in api/docker/properties-builder.sh:
key=${KEY:-}

- in collectors/scm/bitbucket/docker/properties-builder.sh
git.key=${BITBUCKET_KEY:-}

I think that those should be permanently available in those scripts. What do you think? I can create a PR for this if you agree.

Cheers,

Sébastien
column5: Missing properties in properties-builder scripts
column12: 383617649 @spennec - yes I think those should be available permanently.  matthewbeasley

column2:
Hello,
I'm setting up the Jenkins-Cucumber Collector and when I'm launching it, it can't find the cucumber.json.
For my project, the cucumber.json is located in: /target/cucumber/cucumber-report.json 
I tried many expressions in the jenkins-cucumber.cucumberJsonRegex property but It doesn't work.
Here is my cucumber.properties : 

# Database Name
                dbname=dashboarddb

                # Database HostName - default is localhost
                dbhost=localhost

                # Database Port - default is 27017
                dbport=27017

                # Database Username - default is blank
                dbusername=User

                # Database Password - default is blank
                dbpassword=dbpassword

                #Collector schedule (required)
                jenkins-cucumber.cron=0 0/1 * * * *

                #Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
                jenkins-cucumber.servers[0]=http://myjenkins

                jenkins-cucumber.cucumberJsonRegex=${JENKINS_CUCUMBER_JSON_FILENAME:/target/cucumber/cucumber-report.json}

                #Another option: If using same username/password Jenkins auth - set username/apiKey to use HTTP Basic Auth (blank=no auth)
                jenkins-cucumber.username=myUsername
                jenkins-cucumber.apiKey=MyAPI

383689174 @Vijaydaswani configure HYG board in team and let me know if you can see data  nireeshT
383806966 @nireeshT Even after selecting HYG board, there is no data.
![hygboard](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23410287/39167568-6fa57500-47ad-11e8-9dfe-b1af652ae2f2.png)
Please let me know if any changes required. Vijaydaswani
383993789 @Vijaydaswani : Based on what I have seen in the past, check this as well if you could:

1. Check what board name you are getting on the api call below:
https://<jira base url>/rest/agile/1.0/board?name={Your Team Name}

On the response you get back from the above api, make a note of "id" value, which is the board id for your board.

2. And then get the story data for your board using the api call below:
https://<jira base url>/rest/agile/1.0/board/{board id value}/issue

1. See if you are getting any story data at all.
2. In the JSON response, check the field: "customfield_11248"
    See if the value for the "value" property in the body for "customfield_11248" matches your board name. They should match exactly, for the collector to process the issues data coming back from  JIRA. Hope this helps. Thanks !
 subodhbattina

column5: Hygieia Capacity Planning
column12:
381841628 Hi - We need suggestion how best we can do deployment.
My thoughts.
Option [1]
a) Keeping Dashboard, MongoDB in one server
b) Keeping all collectors in one server
Option [2]
a) Keeping Dashboard, MongoDB in one server
b) Keeping all collectors respective component server (Ex) keeping jenkin collector where jenkins is running, keeping sonar collector where sonar is running etc
For both the options, need to know about Linux Server Capacity need.
Please help. Thanks. venkiradkris
381842047 Option [3]
Is it advisable to keep all components of (Collectors, Dashboard, MongoDB) in single server? If so, how about Linux Server Capacity? venkiradkris
383454756 Hi - Any update/help? Thanks. venkiradkris
383631560 @venkiradkris - It's very difficult to quote you a server capacity because your required capacity will depend on your load which will depend on how much you use Hygieia. Your "dashboard for 25 application level CI/CD pipelines." is fairly minimal so you could get away with putting all components on a single server with dual core cpu and 4gb of ram. As your use grows the very first thing I would do is separate the db and everything else. Second step would be to split out the collectors but I doubt you'll ever need to do that.  matthewbeasley
384731219 @venkiradkris - reach out to us on gitter.im if you have further questions. matthewbeasley

column2:
We use the "Board as Team" in our company and I have set up the property in the properties file:
`feature.jiraBoardAsTeam=true`
I have also specified the TeamFieldName customfield to the one we use in our company:
`feature.jiraTeamFieldName=customfield_12300
`

This configuration seems to be correct since the "team" collection gets populated with the boards we have in our company. The problem appears in the "feature" collection in the database. In order to filter the widget information based on boards (or teams), there is the "sTeamId" field in this collection which should represent in which board a given issue belongs to. But, in my case, this field is always null. I have also tried to make an explicit JQL query to the Jira server and to inspect the JSON results and the Board/Team information is inexistent (i.e. null). 

`https://jira.my_company.com/rest/api/2/search?jql=updatedDate%3E%3D%272017-08-01%2019%3A23%27%20AND%20issueType%3D%27Story%27%20ORDER%20BY%20updated%20ASC&fields=*all%2C-comment%2C-watches%2C-worklog%2C-votes%2C-reporter%2C-creator%2C-attachment&maxResults=100&startAt=0
`
 
My jira.properties file:

```
feature.jiraBaseUrl=https://jira.my_company.com
feature.jiraQueryEndpoint=rest/api/2/
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Epic,Story,Bug,Task,Sub-task

logging.file=./logs/jira.log
feature.pageSize=5

feature.deltaStartDate=2017-12-12T00:00:00.000000
feature.masterStartDate=2017-12-12T00:00:00.000000
feature.deltaCollectorItemStartDate=2017-12-12T00:00:00.000000
feature.cron=0 * * * * *
feature.queryFolder=jiraapi-queries
feature.storyQuery=story
feature.epicQuery=epic

feature.jiraCredentials= <my jira credentials here>

feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10007
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10008
feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10005
feature.jiraTeamFieldName=customfield_12300
feature.jiraBoardAsTeam=true

```
**Do you have any idea why this might happen?**

Have a test widget with valid data configured in a team dashboard. 
Do a postman/graphQL request to the dashboardReview endpoint with following parameters

title: <valid dashboard title which has tests configured under Quality Widget>
dashboardType: Team
beginDate: 1514808000 (Unix time, not in milliseconds)
endDate: 1543665600
auditType: TEST_RESULT

**Actual Result**:
`"{

    ],
    "lastUpdated": 0,
    "dashboardTitle": "COAF - LS Bluefin",
    "businessService": "unknown",
    "businessApplication": "unknown",
    "review": {
        "TEST_RESULT": [
            {
                "auditStatuses": [
                    "TEST_RESULT_MISSING"
                ],
                "lastUpdated": 0,
                "lastExecutionTime": 0
            }
        ]

}
`

column2: The script tries to parse the wrong variable, thus never setting the correct host to the db.
column5: Correct parsing of the MONGO_PORT variable
column12:
381323109 Sure! 😊 

In this collector, the properties script expects the full url of the mongo db to be passed in the MONGO_PORT variable. The comment shows the expected format:

Sample: MONGO_PORT=tcp://172.17.0.20:27017

... but it then parses both MONGO_PORT and MONGO_HOST variables. If one follows the comment and passes the full url in the MONGO_PORT variable, then the MONGO_HOST will be empty and the script will end up with an empty mongo host to try to connect to. Or you will need to pass the full url in both variables so that each parsing extracts the correct data.

This is also done in other collectors. See the Gitlab collector's properties [script](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/gitlab/docker/properties-builder.sh
) for instance.

This PR makes this script behave like the other ones, for the sake of coherence in the collectors' configs.

If I may add my 2 cents, I think that it's not a very good way to propagate the url to the docker image. Ideally, the collectors would be configured differently, like the the Sonar collectors whose [script](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/build/sonar/docker/properties-builder.sh) expects two variables for the mongo url: one with the host and another one with the port. That's probably how it should be done. spennec
382409484 @spennec - sonar collector is our target state. I'm going to test this PR today unless you want to go ahead and update this collector to match sonar. matthewbeasley
382441034 I’ve started to work on supporting custom certs in the bitbucket collector, so if it’s ok with you please test and merge this...  spennec

column2:
@tabladrum @nireeshT @satishc1

Hi Guys. 

I am working on Jenkins build to push data to Dashboard. I am using text file to check the status of Deployment " Successful or failed". But the Hygieia plugin only pushes status if the file exists and does not push the results if it does not find the file. Below is my pipeline script. Please let me know what I am not doing correct here.  

**This script works only if the Text file exists. If there is no text file nothing happens.** 
hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Aris', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: '.com', artifactName: '***.txt'**, artifactVersion: '$BUILD_NUMBER', buildStatus: 'Success', environmentName: 'QA'      

**This does not push results if the .txt file does not exist**
hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Aris', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: '.com', artifactName: **'*.txt',** artifactVersion: '$BUILD_NUMBER', buildStatus: 'Failure', environmentName: 'QA'  




**Note**: I can use two different files to determine status of success or failure but its showing the file names on Dashboard. 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26099918/38394336-ea4a0c50-38e2-11e8-9e23-bea7e2e90693.png)
column5: Hygieia pipeline plugin not pushing status if build fails.
column12:
379919249 @nireeshT One more thing which I noticed is the Pipeline is not resetting the artifact number. 

Suppose the 1.3.1.jar is deployed and is successful it is shown on the Pipeline. 
When a next version is pushed the old version is still showing on the Dashboard. Is there a way I can just get rid of the old number. 


![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26099918/38527228-89438e7a-3c0e-11e8-87b1-a7f9825fd5fe.png)

 syedsfayaz
380617411 @syedsfayaz  Build success or failure is all up to Jenkins build status. We do not control the build status, it is result from jenkins.   nireeshT
380618471 @nireeshT I have figured out a work around for this.  Thanks for your support.  syedsfayaz
380643805 @syedsfayaz can you explain what you did for your work around? e-macias
380894457 @nireeshT 
In jenkins for post build notifications. I have setup two post build triggers. I have configured jenkins to push the build status and Build number. So if the build success or fails it calls the post build which pushes the status of Jenkins and build number to Dashboard. 


if ( "$params.BUILD_STATUS" == 'success' ) {
                   echo 'file found'
                   hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Ais', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: 'es.com', artifactName: '$Build_version', artifactVersion: '$Build_version', buildStatus: 'Success', environmentName: 'Dev'
                   hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Ais', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: 'es.com', artifactName: '$Build_version', artifactVersion: '$Build_version', buildStatus: 'Success', environmentName: 'QA'
                  } else {
                   echo 'text file not found'
                   hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Ais', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: 'es.com', artifactName: '$Build_version', artifactVersion: '$Build_version', buildStatus: 'Failure', environmentName: 'Dev'
                   hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'Ais', artifactDirectory: '.', artifactGroup: 'es.com', artifactName: '$Build_version', artifactVersion: '$Build_version', buildStatus: 'Failure', environmentName: 'QA'
                   }


  syedsfayaz
379290930 @syedsfayaz  Pipeline view tracks the progression of application tied to artifact that is deployed across environments. If "Dev.txt" is an artifact built, it can track the same artifact (with same name) deployed in various environments. If artifact is not found in the target location, it does nothing considering no artifact is deployed/deployment failed. Currently Hygieia does not support the incremental versions/ different artifacts in same pipeline flow.  nireeshT
379295222 @nireeshT  So if the artifact is not found in it target(*.jar,*.war) location. Then the build is considered as failed . So it should push the status as failed. I believe that's how you differentiate the Success and failure. ( Green and Red color).
If plugin does nothing if the artifact is not found then we will see only green color on the dashboard.  syedsfayaz
379845365 @nireeshT So I am assuming the same holds true for deploy widget? If no artifact is found, the deploy widget will not update. Is this a correct assumption? e-macias

column2:
Hello,

How is your advice production configuration of a Hygieia instance? Should I use a data container and make it available to others with each collector's configuration files? 

I'm not sure there's a doc page on this subject, but I'd love your take on this.
column5: Questions about prod configuration
column12:
383960938 @spennec - can you describe your intended prod environment in more detail? e.g. cloud or on-prem, windows or linux, how much load do you expect, containers or jars?  matthewbeasley
383969408 Well we can be flexible we it's needed. Up to now, I've found it easier to build and run Hygieia on a linux box, so I expect our production server to also be a Linux box, most probably RHEL7.

Most of our tools are on premise, so we'll connect Hygieia to on premise versions of these services:
- Bitbucket server
- Sonar
- Jenkins
- Jira

Up to now, we have two dashboards that are basically simple POC dashboards, so the instance is run by a simple docker-compose up on the linux box, with the appropriate docker-compose override file at the root dir. spennec
384336775 @spennec My advice would be to centralize your images to provide greater consistency between environments. Building on prod is kinda scary. Btw are you running a standalone docker host or is it clustered? matthewbeasley
384750964 @matthewbeasley oh don't worry, we're not in production yet 😊 For now I only have a single vm in dev with one screen displaying one dashboard... we're still at a POC stage.

How do you inject the configuration? Do you mount a volume in all the images with the properties files already set up?

I think a documentation page explaining the advised prod setup would be a great addition to the wiki… spennec
385000564 @spennec - we currently do not use Docker for our production deployments. There are plans to move to that but other things are taking priority. That being said, in its current state I would mount the properties files as a volume as the ENV vars lack flexibility. I agree that there's a need for explanation of an advised prod setup. matthewbeasley
379979726 @Sbrenthughes @matthewbeasley do you have any advice on the setup to run Hygieia in production? spennec
380227623 Well, I'm working on a production setup, one step is to deploy several
stacks for different clients. The whole architecture is using Docker
containers, so for each client is setting up a stack with the Hygieia
elements ui, API, collectors and a centralized mongo database.

That's the scenario what I'm taking.

Cheers

383969408 Well we can be flexible we it's needed. Up to now, I've found it easier to build and run Hygieia on a linux box, so I expect our production server to also be a Linux box, most probably RHEL7.

Most of our tools are on premise, so we'll connect Hygieia to on premise versions of these services:
- Bitbucket server
- Sonar
- Jenkins
- Jira

Up to now, we have two dashboards that are basically simple POC dashboards, so the instance is run by a simple docker-compose up on the linux box, with the appropriate docker-compose override file at the root dir. spennec
384336775 @spennec My advice would be to centralize your images to provide greater consistency between environments. Building on prod is kinda scary. Btw are you running a standalone docker host or is it clustered? matthewbeasley
384750964 @matthewbeasley oh don't worry, we're not in production yet 😊 For now I only have a single vm in dev with one screen displaying one dashboard... we're still at a POC stage.

How do you inject the configuration? Do you mount a volume in all the images with the properties files already set up?

I think a documentation page explaining the advised prod setup would be a great addition to the wiki… spennec
385000564 @spennec - we currently do not use Docker for our production deployments. There are plans to move to that but other things are taking priority. That being said, in its current state I would mount the properties files as a volume as the ENV vars lack flexibility. I agree that there's a need for explanation of an advised prod setup. matthewbeasley

I get a permission denied error from nginx when running the image. Clearing the site data or cookies it not sufficient. If I open a bash in the running image, I can see that the html folder is owned by nginx but all its files belong to root. Chowning them to nginx solves the problem.

column2:
Hi, 
Should the properties for the collectors be placed in separate files (Eg.  D:\Hygieia\collectors\scm\github\github.properties) or should they be placed within the dashboard.properties file found within (D:\Hygieia\api\dashboard.properties).?

Should i configure the application.properties file found within D:\Hygieia-Test\Hygieia\api\src\main\resources?

I've installed my Dashboard by creating a separate dashboard.properties file within D:\Hygieia\api\ and  creating a separate github.properties file within D:\Hygieia\collectors\scm\github\. The API , UI and collectors run fine but have I installed it the right way or have I made a mistake?
column5: Installation Confusion
column12:
376865472 sound good to me. Dinnerspy
376880342 @Avfdo1994 - it's totally up to you where you put your properties file and up to you whether you use a single file or not. The command line arg '--spring.config.prefix' used when starting up the jar tells you which properties to use in the specified file. 

Personally, since I often destroy and reclone my repo I have my properties files in a centralized location that is not in the project. I recommend this if you plan to work on the project since it will keep your `git status` clean. Mine are in `~/dev/config/`. @satishc1 recommended this to me and it's worked great so far.  matthewbeasley
377129436 @matthewbeasley so just to be clear --spring.config.prefix does not refer to the file name say for example --spring.config.prefix=bitbucket means it looks for a properties file that's named bitbucket.properties?  Avfdo1994
377213438 @Avfdo1994 the --spring.config.location= tells it what properties to use. Dinnerspy

column2:
Seems like the maven build and docker build do not use the same Dockerfiles. In the score plugin, the docker files use different names for the properties-builder script. In the project, the file is named "properties-builder.sh", like in the other projects, so I changed the incorrect Dockerfile.

By the way, this was making a mvn install fail on my Mac... not sure it was not detected earlier.
column5: Mismatch between Dockerfiles and properties builder script on file names

column5: Gitlab collector not picking up my repos despite correct properties file

column2:
Hello,

I've configured the docker.compose override to provided the following properties to the jenkins-build-collector:

Properties file created Tue Mar 27 07:24:21 UTC 2018:  config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties         
Note: passwords & apiKey hidden                                                                                  

#Database Name                                                                                                   
dbname=dashboarddb                                                                                               
                                                                                                                 
#Database HostName - default is localhost                                                                        
dbhost=db                                                                                                        
                                                                                                                 
#Database Port - default is 27017                                                                                
dbport=27017                                                                                                     
                                                                                                                 
#Database Username - default is blank                                                                            
dbusername=dashboarduser


Despite this config, that works correctly to connect the api to the mongo instance, I see the following error:

2018-03-27 07:24:27,059 INFO  org.mongodb.driver.cluster - Exception in monitor thread while connecting to server localhost:27017                   
com.mongodb.MongoSocketOpenException: Exception opening socket                                                                                      
        at com.mongodb.connection.SocketStream.open(SocketStream.java:63) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]                                       
        at com.mongodb.connection.InternalStreamConnection.open(InternalStreamConnection.java:114) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na]              
        at com.mongodb.connection.DefaultServerMonitor$ServerMonitorRunnable.run(DefaultServerMonitor.java:127) ~[mongo-java-driver-3.0.2.jar!/:na] 
        at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:748) [na:1.8.0_162]                                                                                     
Caused by: java.net.ConnectException: Connection refused (Connection refused)                                                                       
        at java.net.PlainSocketImpl.socketConnect(Native Method) ~[na:1.8.0_162]                                                                    
           
I think that the problem comes from the mongo client that did not read the properties, since it's trying to configure a connection to localhost instread of db:

2018-03-27 07:24:26,905 INFO  c.c.dashboard.config.MongoConfig - Initializing Mongo Client server at: localhost:27017

The mongo instance is running, the api can connect to it:

2018-03-27 07:00:44,985 INFO  org.mongodb.driver.connection - Opened connection [connectionId{localValue:5, serverValue:11}] to db:27017

What am I doing wrong? :) 

Thanks a lot for your help!

376766839 @matthewbeasley a quick question on the open-sourceness of this project :)... 

Is it maintained by capital one? Or mainly by the community? If we spend some time fixing a few things (bugs, configs, ...) will it actually end up in the master branch or will we need to maintain a fork?

At this moment, I've built a simple dashboard (jenkins + sonar) but have seen quite a bit of little things that do not work. For instance, 500 max projects are downloaded from Sonar. I'd be happy to help correct that but only if this actually goes in the master's branch (obviously, only if the patch is ok in terms of code quality, etc...).

Can you tell me more about all this?

Thanks a lot! spennec
376887886 @spennec - It's so open-source ;). 

It's maintained primarily by Capital One. We have partnerships with other companies who contribute as well: recently Walmart, American Airlines and Single Stone (excuse the name drops). If you submit a PR and it's solid, it will definitely be merged in. We're a relatively small team, so we get very excited about contributions from the community. 

If you're interested in putting in work, reach out to me on [gitter.im](https://gitter.im/capitalone/Hygieia) or email me at beardsley.ma at gmail.com and we can work together to ensure your contribution goes smoothly matthewbeasley
376890603 Great news!

I'm trying to build some motivation for this in my company and we'll see how we can collaborate. Thanks for the info. spennec
377286860 @spennec if you are good here can you close this? Sbrenthughes
423039676 OMG, I should have found this one before I spent two days on debugging Jenkins collector T_T xpdable
376477641 One thing strikes me in the properties script:

if [ "$MONGO_PORT" != "" ]; then                                           
        # Sample: MONGO_PORT=tcp://172.17.0.20:27017                       
        MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_HOST|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`  
        MONGODB_PORT=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\2;'`  
else ....

This does work... the first line should be:
MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`  
... otherwise the MONGO_PORT property is not parsed at all to extract the host. spennec
376486456 Ok got it.

The Dockerfile always expects the property files to be named "application.properties", but the properties-builder script sometimes outputs the props in another file.

You have to provide a TEST_SCRIPT value in the docker-compose override, otherwise it doesn't start the spring app with the correct properties.

@matthewbeasley I don't know if you have seen this, but that seems buggy to me...  spennec
376518034 @spennec - I have seen it. It's actually something that there's an on-going effort to fix. We've basically been correcting one collector at a time when we get the opportunity. The target state is that the properties-builder.sh files contain a minimal amount of properties to get the container running in a development environment. For production it's recommended to mount your properties files as a volume. 

The [Github graphql collector](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github-graphql/docker/properties-builder.sh) is a good example. If you are interested in making this change to the jenkins collector (or any collector for that matter) and submitting a PR, I'd love to review it.  matthewbeasley
376518544 @spennec - we'd also be interested in a solution that rids us of the properties-builder.sh file altogether. matthewbeasley
376518897 Hello,

For the moment, I'm just making a POC to show what dashboarding could bring to our dev teams. If we go forward with this, I'll contribute as much as I can. spennec

376561765 Hi not sure if this will help as im having issues with gitlab my self. But you github.properties file should be called application.properties and should have the variable from the template bellow. Comment out what your are not using and edit to your values.

		# Database Name
		dbname=dashboarddb

		# Database HostName - default is localhost
		dbhost=localhost

		# Database Port - default is 27017
		dbport=27017

		# MongoDB replicaset
		dbreplicaset=[false if you are not using MongoDB replicaset]
		dbhostport=[host1:port1,host2:port2,host3:port3]

		# Database Username - default is blank
		dbusername=dashboarduser

		# Database Password - default is blank
		dbpassword=dbpassword

		# Logging File location
		logging.file=./logs/github.log

		# Collector schedule (required)
		github.cron=0 0/5 * * * *

		github.host=github.com

		# Maximum number of previous days from current date, when fetching commits
		github.commitThresholdDays=15

    # Optional: Error threshold count after which collector stops collecting for a collector item. Default is 2.
    github.errorThreshold=1

    # This is the key generated using the Encryption class in core
    github.key=<your-generated-key>

    # Personal access token generated from github and used for making authentiated calls
    github.personalAccessToken=

 [Source](http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/github.html)
 Dinnerspy
377290441 @Dinnerspy  if you are using gitlab, use gitlab prop file.  Your props should have below props

gitlab.cron=5 * * * * *
gitlab.host=gitlab.XXXXcom
gitlab.protocol=https
gitlab.apiToken=XXXXX
 nireeshT

java -jar github-scm-collector-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=../github.properties
 nireeshT

column2:
Hello,

I'm making a POC with Hygieia, and I've had the following problem: when I call the UI in a browser (http://myhost:3000), I get a 403 Forbidden error. In the UI docker image, I see many of the following logs:

2018/03/23 11:08:34 [error] 9#9: *1 open() "/usr/share/nginx/html/favicon.ico" failed (13: Permission denied), client: x.y.z., server: localhost, request: "GET /favicon.ico HTTP/1.1", host: "remotehost:3000", referrer: "http://remotehost:3000/"

I build everything straight from Github's master branch, on a RHEL box. I build the docker images, by following this documentation: http://capitalone.github.io/Hygieia/builddocker.html

After a bit of surfing, it seems that the problem is that nginx's user doesn't have the correct rights on the served files: https://github.com/docker-library/docs/issues/883

I tried several chown and chmod but it seems not to work... 

Can anybody help?

Thanks a lot,

Sébastien
column5: Permission denied when connecting to UI
column12:
376892529 @spennec - I'm not sure that's necessary. Shouldn't the nginx image already be the owner of that directory? matthewbeasley
376903434 What I've seen is that the directory is owned by nginx but all the files inside belong to root. Changing them to nginx seems to solve the problem. Didn't want to open a PR for this because it's my first time using nginx, so I might be wrong. spennec
377229249 @spennec - yea that totally makes sense. Mind submitting another PR to add the chown to both files? matthewbeasley
377229711 ok will do. Just for my understanding: it seems like the docker files at the root are the "real" ones, that you can use with a docker-compose. Those in the docker subdirectories seem linked to the maven plugin that you want to get rid of, right? spennec
377276380 @spennec that's correct. matthewbeasley
375715960 @spennec - this is typically a cookie issue. Can you go to [chrome://settings/siteData](chrome://settings/siteData) - search for localhost and delete that cookie.  matthewbeasley
375716820 @spennec - when you search make sure you are searching the cookies and not the settings. That part trips me up fairly often matthewbeasley
375882126 That solved the issue, thanks a lot! Now bumping into another problem but probably totally unrelated, so I'll open another issue. spennec
376078531 Ouch sorry: the problem was actually solved by two things:
- cleaning site data
- modifying the UI's dockerfiles (UI/Dockerfile and UI/docker/Dockerfile) to include this line:

chown -R nginx:nginx /usr/share/nginx/html/

@matthewbeasley  do you think this should be corrected in master? spennec
376892529 @spennec - I'm not sure that's necessary. Shouldn't the nginx image already be the owner of that directory? matthewbeasley
376903434 What I've seen is that the directory is owned by nginx but all the files inside belong to root. Changing them to nginx seems to solve the problem. Didn't want to open a PR for this because it's my first time using nginx, so I might be wrong. spennec

378554156 Have a similar issue. Seems that the team and project in the GitLab API should be an id. When you use the team field only the group api is used. When team en project are used the project api is used. But when both are used the team and project field content is combined. The api cannot handle that either.

https://gitlab url/api/v4/groups -> shows all groups
https://gitlab url/api/v4/projects -> shows all projects
Adding a / with an id of one of the groups or projects provides more detail. This is what the collector should use to retreive information I guess? pversteijnen

column2:
This PR removes much of the complexity from the sonar collector's properties-builder.sh file. This is beneficial in that users looking to set up Hygieia via docker-compose for development / evaluation can do so without having to set a bunch of ENV vars. Users wishing to use the sonar collector container for production can simply mount their properties file as a volume. 

This PR also updates the score collector setup to be more inline with the other collectors.

To test do these steps:
1: run `mvn clean install`
2: have a local sonar instance available on localhost:9000
3: run `docker-compose up -d`
4: run `docker ps` and locate the sonar collector
5: run `docker logs {name-of-sonar-collector}` replacing {name-of-sonar-collector} with the name from step 4

Hello,
I've been trying to configure static analysis to the quality widget but so far without success. 

Our static analysis results is being generated through Eslint and the output is in checkstyle format. In our job we're publishing this checkstyle results using the checkstyle plygin and the results are available through Jenkins rest api.

The issue is that this data is not showing in our dashboard or in mongodb. I'm wodering how can I import checkstyle static analysis to hygieia.

Bellow some information about our environment:

**code quality properties:**
#pattern to find cucubmer reports
#jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex[0]=${JENKINS_CODEQUALITY_JSON_FILENAME:-test.xml}
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.junit=${JENKINS_CODEQUALITY_JUNIT_FILENAME:-TEST-.*\\.xml}

column2:
Hi!

I am configuring Artifactory collector and it reads repos but doens't try to fetch any information about artifacts.

My version of Hygieia Artifactory Collector is 2.0.5.

My config is:

```
dbname=dashboard
artifactory.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
artifactory.servers[0]=https://artifactory-qa.acme.net/
artifactory.usernames[0]=dmitry
artifactory.apiKeys[0]=some_key
artifactory.repos[0]=BPM_Artifacts
artifactory.endpoint=artifactory/
artifactory.patterns[0]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>\\k<module>)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
artifactory.patterns[1]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>ivy)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?\\.(?<ext>xml)
artifactory.patterns[2]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<type>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>[^\\.-/]+)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard.collector=DEBUG
```

In the log I see:

```
Mar 13 13:35:00 hygieia java[25973]: 2018-03-13 13:35:00,064 DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultArtifactoryClient - repoName:BPM_Artifacts
Mar 13 13:35:00 hygieia java[25973]: 2018-03-13 13:35:00,064 DEBUG c.c.d.c.DefaultArtifactoryClient - repoURL: https://artifactory-qa.acme.net/artifactory/BPM_Artifacts
```

And that's all. Collector doesn't try to pickup any information about artifacts. At the same time, repo contains about 6000 artifacts.

column2: Allows the admin to configure the servers and credentials with which the collectors will fetch the data. Collector changes for Nexus-iq-collector and Jenkins-build collector.

column12:
380943983 @Satheesh-Balachandran  Can you detail how we can use this configuration once it is saved to Mongo. I see a record generated in Configuration collection, what's the purpose of that configuration item. nireeshT
381043239 The config data(url, username, password) will be fetched from each collectors on each run. If the password for a particular tool, say rally, changes at any time, it need not have to be changed in the application.properties. The admin can just change this in the configuration page UI(#2073 ) and without restarting the collector, the changes will be adapted automatically.  Satheesh-Balachandran

390574615 @pk277 I had the same issue when updated from 2.0.4 to 2.0.5. The only solution I found is to drop the entire DB in mongo and re-collect all data. After this everything works as intended. 0-d
